From: Dr. Oscar P. Larghi <oplarghi@drwebsa.com.ar>

A previous post explained that smearing vampire bats is done to spread the
anti-coagulant among other individuals of this species residing in their
refuges and to reduce population. Vaccinating USEFUL carriers and
susceptible species, as cattle, prevents rabies. Vampire bats do not fit in
the first category because they belong to a synantropic species. This
disease is the only natural population control method for vampire bats.
Vaccinating them would most likely produce a population explosion (1), an
effect nobody would like and more so "ganaderos"[ranchers in Spanish in
the affected areas of Latin America.
"Ganaderos" know very well the direct damage, other than rabies, produced
by vampire bat bites (1, 2) such as the asthenic [related to asthenia
syndrome characterized by weakness, weight loss, dehydration, as well as
myiasis, [any disease due to the presence of the larvae of flies scars
which in sows prevent feeding of their litters, etc.(3).
References:
1) Delpietro HA, RG Russo, 1996, Aspectos ecológicos y epidemiológicos de
la agresión del vampiro y de la rabia paralítica en la Argentina y análisis
de las propuestas efectuadas para su control.1996. Rev. sci. tech. Off.
int. Epiz. 15: 971-984.
2) Kverno NB, GC Mitchell. Los murciélagos vampiros y la producción
pecuaria wn América Latina, 1976, Rev. Mund. Zoot. 17:1.
3) Delpietro HA, RG Russo, HHG Schweieters, 1999, Observaciones sobre el
ataque del vampiro común _Desmodus rotundus_ al ganado en el norte de la
Argentina. Rev. Med. Vet. 80:460-464.
